<p>% 𝚫 = percentage change in that particular demographic only (calculated using 𝚫/previous year)</p>
<p>So while we have to take into account that this is fairly soft data, it does raise the possibility that we're actually seeing our ratios evening out over time- Most of the 2014-15 decrease was from the male-identifying demographic, and for 2015, only the &quot;other&quot; identification had a % 𝚫 greatly outside of the norm. This may be related to the massive spike that demographic experienced in 2015: If we figure, say, half of those 78 new people hung around for a while and lost interest, that actually accounts for about 20% of that contingent's 2016 losses, putting them at around the same % 𝚫 as the other identifications. Over 2014-2016, it actually works out to a net gain.</p>
<p>I'd venture that the lower-than-the-mean reduction in our male contingent in 2015-16 may be related to the noted surge in readership coming from YouTube- Let's Players are known to be a major pipeline for the site, and their demographics skew somewhat toward teenage and young adult males. That's probably a major factor in the skewed ratios, given that the male demographic saw both the largest 𝚫 <em>and</em> % 𝚫 over the two-year period: young guys and a slightly lower number of gals finding the site through a Lets Play, hanging around for a while, then losing interest, with a new surge coming with each new let's play- but that's fading as time goes on.</p>
<p>I'm also really interested to see what happens with the increased deviantArt presence, as that site skews slightly more towards nerdettes than nerds.</p>
